DAWAI:  Well, you already know the answer, but you know, this...cultivating  is provisional, and according to the previous yanas, before Dzogchen.  But Dzogchen sees that sort of as splashing around in the water, right?  It seems like you're cultivating it, but it's all already compassion, so, you don't need to...You can't really cultivate, and Dzogchen specifically is antithetical to cultivation.  They definitely have those terms, and utilize those methods, and they can help people, perhaps, be kinder, and tune in to their natural compassion, but we want to be relentless---at least if you're following it according to my opinion---we want to be relentless with... that we already have our compassion there.  We know it, it's familiar to us.  And so, when our contractions fall away, that's what's left over:  our natural kindness.  And it could take awhile to become less disgruntled, or less aggravated about situations that we have on our mind, right?  That could take awhile. Parental situations tend to bug us, cultural situations really can ignite us into echoes, feelings, that we hold onto, thoughts we hold onto, clouding our natural compassion, that absolute bodhicitta, right?  So here, definitely,  Dzogchen is synonymous with absolute bodhicitta, rather than this aspirational which they would have in the Mahayana. And then the Shravakayana, they don't care about nobody but themselves...No, I'm just kidding, they also have the loving kindness practice.  

